WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.220 --> 00:00:06.180
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:06.180 --> 00:00:07.530
&gt;&gt; Karen Lloyd: It's
my distinct pleasure

00:00:07.530 --> 00:00:09.780
to introduce you our next speaker.

00:00:09.780 --> 00:00:14.150
Admiral Stavridis is a retired Navy
Admiral who is currently the Dean

00:00:14.150 --> 00:00:18.150
of the Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy at Tufts University.

00:00:18.150 --> 00:00:21.870
He has commanded at all levels of
the military to include; Commander,

00:00:21.870 --> 00:00:25.280
European Command, and as
Supreme Allied Commander Europe.

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.500
I could provide you with a long
list of his military assignments,

00:00:29.500 --> 00:00:32.680
but you have probably already
looked them up on the internet.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.950 position:56%
So instead I will share some nuggets
that provide a better understanding

00:00:36.950 --> 00:00:40.870
of how his career places him
at the Book Festival today.

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:42.650
He is no stranger to books.

00:00:42.650 --> 00:00:45.840
He started his love of books
while his family was stationed

00:00:45.840 --> 00:00:48.630
in Greece in the early 60s.

00:00:48.630 --> 00:00:53.050
Because there was no Armed Forces
network television he sent his time

00:00:53.050 --> 00:00:54.930
at the post library.

00:00:54.930 --> 00:00:57.150
Now I can totally relate to this.

00:00:57.150 --> 00:01:00.960
My family was in France at that
same time and my whole family,

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:05.290
all seven kids, were over
at the post library too.

00:01:05.290 --> 00:01:06.900
What is striking to book lovers is

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:11.020
that throughout his Naval career
Admiral Stavridis published either

00:01:11.020 --> 00:01:16.200 position:56%
articles or books at each successive
rank to include midshipman.

00:01:16.200 --> 00:01:19.160
I suggest he would tell you his
favorite assignment was command

00:01:19.160 --> 00:01:21.700
of destroyer USS Fary.

00:01:21.700 --> 00:01:24.550
[phonetic] It came about as a
result of his daily journaling,

00:01:24.550 --> 00:01:27.840
using a typewriter of all
things, during his two

00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:30.210
and a half years onboard ship.

00:01:30.210 --> 00:01:35.330
The result was a compilation of a
sense of wondering and mistakes,

00:01:35.330 --> 00:01:38.220
all of which were intended
to convey, while his time

00:01:38.220 --> 00:01:43.120 position:56%
in command was successful, not every
day was fabulous and the real point

00:01:43.120 --> 00:01:47.970
of life is not what you accomplish,
but rather what you overcome.

00:01:47.970 --> 00:01:50.350
In his most recent
book, "Sea Power,"

00:01:50.350 --> 00:01:54.900
Admiral Stavridis uses his Naval
experience to guide us on a journey

00:01:54.900 --> 00:01:56.750
through the seas of the world.

00:01:56.750 --> 00:02:01.100
He asks us to consider the value
and the challenge the seas,

00:02:01.100 --> 00:02:05.080
from both a personal and an
international economic system.

00:02:05.080 --> 00:02:06.970
He helps us understand
the significance

00:02:06.970 --> 00:02:10.020 position:56%
of sea control and power projection.

00:02:10.020 --> 00:02:14.200
He asks that we be mindful of
the geopolitics of the ocean,

00:02:14.200 --> 00:02:17.600
while warning us not to
over imagine the importance

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:20.370
of our own small voyages on earth.

00:02:20.370 --> 00:02:22.820
Please join me in welcoming
a great friend of the Library

00:02:22.820 --> 00:02:25.510
of Congress; Admiral
James Stavridis.

00:02:25.510 --> 00:02:35.910
[ Applause ]

00:02:35.910 --> 00:02:37.210
&gt;&gt; Admiral James Stavridis:
Thank you.

00:02:37.210 --> 00:02:39.530
Thank you and I very much
appreciate everybody coming

00:02:39.530 --> 00:02:41.500
out on this drizzly day.

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:45.060
It's kind of a mariner's
day out there I would say.

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:51.380
Normally when people hear that
marvelous biography introduction --

00:02:51.380 --> 00:02:52.800
thank you Karen [assumed
spelling] --

00:02:52.800 --> 00:02:56.620
the first thing they say when they
actually see me is, "You know,

00:02:56.620 --> 00:03:00.630
I thought you'd be taller
than you appear to be."

00:03:00.630 --> 00:03:04.340 position:56%
[laughter] Well, what I'd like to do
today is just show you a few images,

00:03:04.340 --> 00:03:06.430
and we can go to the
first slide please.

00:03:06.430 --> 00:03:09.790
We're just going to talk about
the oceans and we're going to take

00:03:09.790 --> 00:03:15.830
about 15 minutes and kind of walk
through the oceans of the world.

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:20.550
And then we'll consider,
in the second 15 minutes,

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:22.080
what we ought to do about it

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:25.990
and what are the importance
of these oceans.

00:03:25.990 --> 00:03:31.680
So let me begin with a line
the British Royal Navy uses,

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:35.860
which is that the sea is one.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:39.130 position:56%
The sea is one, meaning it connects.

00:03:39.130 --> 00:03:43.940
And most who don't spend a
lot of time on the oceans --

00:03:43.940 --> 00:03:50.640 position:56%
and I spent 37 years in the Navy, 11
years day for day on the deep ocean

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:56.950
in that time -- don't consider that
70 percent of the world is water.

00:03:56.950 --> 00:04:04.230
And by the way, 70 percent of
your body is water and 70 percent

00:04:04.230 --> 00:04:11.850 position:56%
of the oxygen that you breathe comes
from photosynthesis in the oceans.

00:04:11.850 --> 00:04:20.280
And -- next slide please -- 95
percent of the world's trade --

00:04:20.280 --> 00:04:26.050 position:56%
the lifeblood of the earth's economy
-- passes across those oceans.

00:04:26.050 --> 00:04:31.600
On any given day 50,000
ships at sea,

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:36.400
three to five million
mariners at sea.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:41.290
This is an extraordinary,
complex ecosystem,

00:04:41.290 --> 00:04:46.650
both in the ecological sense
and the economic sense.

00:04:46.650 --> 00:04:50.470
And to give you one last image to
hold in your head about the size

00:04:50.470 --> 00:04:56.040
of the oceans, consider this;
you could take all of the land

00:04:56.040 --> 00:05:01.560
in the world and it would fit
quite nicely inside the Pacific

00:05:01.560 --> 00:05:03.660
Ocean alone.

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:10.090
So the seas are in many ways
fundamental to the earth.

00:05:10.090 --> 00:05:12.310
Well, let's get underway.

00:05:12.310 --> 00:05:14.630
Let's start in the Pacific.

00:05:14.630 --> 00:05:20.000
This is a 1589 antiquarian
chart made

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.300
by Ortelius, a Dutch cartographer.

00:05:23.300 --> 00:05:27.420
And you see the discontinuities
and the misunderstandings

00:05:27.420 --> 00:05:29.960
of the outline of the Pacific.

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:37.350
But I'd invite you to go back 4,000
years before that chart was made,

00:05:37.350 --> 00:05:43.180
bottom right, the voyages of the
Polynesians who traversed six,

00:05:43.180 --> 00:05:50.380
seven, 8,000 nautical miles,
three, 4,000 years ago.

00:05:50.380 --> 00:05:57.200
These are ancient seas and none
is more ancient than the Pacific.

00:05:57.200 --> 00:05:59.890
In the American mental map

00:05:59.890 --> 00:06:03.280
of the Pacific this is
what we tend to see, right?

00:06:03.280 --> 00:06:04.890
It's the second World War

00:06:04.890 --> 00:06:10.730
when a vast American armada
sails across it by 1945.

00:06:10.730 --> 00:06:16.260 position:56%
In this period we have more aircraft
carriers than we have ships today.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:21.260
The sea is covered by the
United States and we still sort

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:26.110
of see ourselves as a
preeminent Pacific maritime power.

00:06:26.110 --> 00:06:31.120
But let's look back at
China's history in these seas.

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:33.600
Here are two vessels.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:36.290
The little one on the left,

00:06:36.290 --> 00:06:40.160
you'll recall from your grade
school studies, the Nina,

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:43.070
the Pinta, and the Santa Maria.

00:06:43.070 --> 00:06:45.510
The little one is a
model of the Santa Maria

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:49.990
that Christopher Columbus
sailed in 1492.

00:06:49.990 --> 00:06:56.940
That massive ship behind it, built
in roughly the same time period,

00:06:56.940 --> 00:07:00.750
was the flagship of
Chinese Admiral Jang Hi.

00:07:00.750 --> 00:07:04.800
[assumed spelling] It was, as
you can see, 10 times the size

00:07:04.800 --> 00:07:10.530
