had a hidden temperate zone in it.

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:50.700
This is just over a
hundred years ago.

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:53.890
The Jeanette tried to
get through the ice,

00:15:53.890 --> 00:15:58.150
was frozen in place,
many of its crew died.

00:15:58.150 --> 00:16:03.350
Today the Arctic is
a little less icy.

00:16:03.350 --> 00:16:07.690
Here's a news flash;
global warming is real.

00:16:07.690 --> 00:16:11.430
[laughter] The ice is
melting and it's going to open

00:16:11.430 --> 00:16:16.490
that northern trade route,
increase geopolitical competition,

00:16:16.490 --> 00:16:18.660
uncover hydrocarbons.

00:16:18.660 --> 00:16:20.210
On one side is Russia.

00:16:20.210 --> 00:16:24.000
On the other side are
five NATO nations.

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:26.810
The Arctic has never seen war.

00:16:26.810 --> 00:16:31.870
It will be our challenge to
ensure that we can continue to say

00:16:31.870 --> 00:16:34.590
that as the century unfolds.

00:16:34.590 --> 00:16:38.730
If we are able to say it, it will
be the result of organizations

00:16:38.730 --> 00:16:43.060 position:56%
like this; the Arctic Council, which
brings together Russia and NATO,

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:48.370 position:56%
one of the few places we have a
coherent conversation at the moment.

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:51.130
The United States needs
to up its game.

00:16:51.130 --> 00:16:56.670
I'm showing a picture of the one
operational icebreaker the US has.

00:16:56.670 --> 00:17:02.180
Denmark, a nation of five
million, operates six icebreakers.

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:05.250
We need to improve
ourselves in this zone.

00:17:05.250 --> 00:17:08.540
So those are the oceans.

00:17:08.540 --> 00:17:10.350
